{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018csamVsp3fwzprqNZkzgE5","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 3.3: Onboard Alias\n     2→\n     3→Status: verifying\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As an operator,\n    10→I want `codeharness onboard` to work the same as `codeharness audit`,\n    11→so that existing scripts and docs don't break when the audit command replaces onboard.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→1. **Given** `codeharness onboard` is run with no subcommand and no flags, **When** it executes, **Then** it produces identical output to `codeharness audit` (same dimension checks, same status/metric format, same exit code). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→2. **Given** `codeharness onboard --fix` is run, **When** it executes, **Then** it produces identical output and behavior to `codeharness audit --fix` (generates fix stories for gaps, updates sprint state). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→3. **Given** `codeharness onboard --json` is run, **When** it executes, **Then** it produces identical JSON output to `codeharness audit --json` (same structure, same fields). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→4. **Given** `codeharness onboard --fix --json` is run, **When** it executes, **Then** it produces identical output to `codeharness audit --fix --json` (includes `fixStories` array in JSON). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→5. **Given** the harness is not initialized, **When** `codeharness onboard` is run, **Then** it exits with `[FAIL] Harness not initialized -- run codeharness init first` and exit code 1 — same as `codeharness audit`. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→6. **Given** `codeharness onboard scan` is run, **When** it executes, **Then** it prints a deprecation warning `[WARN] 'onboard scan' is deprecated — use 'codeharness audit' instead` and then runs the audit command (maps legacy subcommand to new behavior). <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→7. **Given** the old `registerOnboardCommand` function, **When** the alias is implemented, **Then** the old onboard command registration is removed from `src/index.ts` and replaced by the alias registration, so there is no duplicate command registration. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    22→8. **Given** `codeharness --help` is run, **When** the help output is displayed, **Then** both `audit` and `onboard` appear in the command list, with `onboard` described as `Alias for audit — check all compliance dimensions`. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    23→\n    24→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    25→\n    26→- [x] Task 1: Rewrite `src/commands/onboard.ts` as a thin alias (AC: #1, #2, #3, #4, #5, #6, #7, #8)\n    27→  - [x] 1.1: Remove all existing scan/coverage/audit/epic subcommand logic, shared state, and formatting helpers from `src/commands/onboard.ts`\n    28→  - [x] 1.2: Implement `registerOnboardCommand(program)` that creates a `program.command('onboard')` with description `'Alias for audit — check all compliance dimensions'`\n    29→  - [x] 1.3: Mirror the `--json` and `--fix` options from the audit command\n    30→  - [x] 1.4: In the action handler, delegate directly to the same logic as `registerAuditCommand` by calling the audit action internals (either extract shared handler or import and call `runAudit` / `generateFixStories` / `addFixStoriesToState` / formatting directly)\n    31→  - [x] 1.5: Add deprecated `scan` subcommand that prints `[WARN] 'onboard scan' is deprecated — use 'codeharness audit' instead` then runs audit logic (AC #6)\n    32→\n    33→- [x] Task 2: Extract shared audit action handler (AC: #1, #2, #3, #4, #5)\n    34→  - [x] 2.1: Extract the audit action logic from `src/commands/audit.ts` into a shared function `executeAudit(opts: { isJson: boolean; isFix: boolean }): Promise<void>` in a new file `src/commands/audit-action.ts` (or keep inline if both commands can import the same handler)\n    35→  - [x] 2.2: Have both `registerAuditCommand` and `registerOnboardCommand` use the same handler, ensuring identical behavior\n    36→  - [x] 2.3: Keep `registerAuditCommand` in `src/commands/audit.ts` unchanged (or with minimal refactor to use extracted handler)\n    37→\n    38→- [x] Task 3: Update `src/index.ts` registration (AC: #7)\n    39→  - [x] 3.1: Verify `registerOnboardCommand(program)` is still called in `src/index.ts` — the function name stays the same, only the implementation changes\n    40→  - [x] 3.2: Verify no duplicate `audit` or `onboard` commands are registered\n    41→\n    42→- [x] Task 4: Remove dead code (AC: #7)\n    43→  - [x] 4.1: Remove imports for `scanCodebase`, `analyzeCoverageGaps`, `auditDocumentation` from `src/lib/scanner.js` if no longer used elsewhere\n    44→  - [x] 4.2: Remove imports for `generateOnboardingEpic`, `writeOnboardingEpic`, `formatEpicSummary`, `promptApproval`, `importOnboardingEpic` from `src/lib/epic-generator.js` if no longer used elsewhere\n    45→  - [x] 4.3: Remove imports for `listIssues`, `createIssue` from `src/lib/beads.js` (onboard no longer calls beads directly)\n    46→  - [x] 4.4: Remove imports for `filterTrackedGaps`, `findVerificationGaps`, `findPerFileCoverageGaps`, `findObservabilityGaps`, `getOnboardingProgress` from `src/lib/onboard-checks.js` if no longer used\n    47→  - [x] 4.5: Remove imports for `saveScanCache`, `loadValidCache` from `src/lib/scan-cache.js` if no longer used\n    48→  - [x] 4.6: Remove imports for `appendOnboardingEpicToSprint` from `src/lib/beads-sync.js` if no longer used\n    49→  - [x] 4.7: Check all removed imports — do NOT delete the library files themselves, only remove the imports from `onboard.ts`. Other commands may still use them.\n    50→\n    51→- [x] Task 5: Update tests (AC: all)\n    52→  - [x] 5.1: Rewrite `src/commands/__tests__/onboard.test.ts` to test the alias behavior:\n    53→    - Test `codeharness onboard` delegates to audit logic\n    54→    - Test `codeharness onboard --fix` delegates to audit --fix logic\n    55→    - Test `codeharness onboard --json` produces same output as audit --json\n    56→    - Test `codeharness onboard scan` prints deprecation warning and runs audit\n    57→    - Test precondition failure (harness not initialized) produces same error as audit\n    58→  - [x] 5.2: Mock the same dependencies as `audit.test.ts` (runPreconditions, runAudit, formatAuditHuman, formatAuditJson, generateFixStories, addFixStoriesToState)\n    59→  - [x] 5.3: Verify the `--help` output includes both `audit` and `onboard` commands\n    60→  - [x] 5.4: Target 100% coverage on the rewritten `onboard.ts`\n    61→\n    62→- [x] Task 6: Build and verify (AC: all)\n    63→  - [x] 6.1: Run `npm run build` — verify tsup compiles successfully\n    64→  - [x] 6.2: Run `npm run test:unit` — all tests pass, no regressions\n    65→  - [x] 6.3: Verify no file exceeds 300 lines (NFR9) — rewritten `onboard.ts` should be ~40-60 lines\n    66→  - [x] 6.4: Verify `codeharness onboard` runs end-to-end and produces audit output\n    67→  - [x] 6.5: Verify `codeharness audit` still works identically (no regression)\n    68→  - [x] 6.6: Verify `codeharness --help` shows both commands\n    69→\n    70→## Dev Notes\n    71→\n    72→### Architecture References\n    73→\n    74→This story implements FR16 (`onboard` becomes alias for `audit`). It replaces the old onboard command (which had its own scan/coverage/audit/epic pipeline) with a thin alias that delegates to the new audit coordinator from Story 3.1/3.2.\n    75→\n    76→### Key Implementation Details\n    77→\n    78→**Alias, not duplicate:** The onboard command must produce byte-identical output to audit. The cleanest approach is to extract the audit action handler into a shared function and call it from both commands. Do NOT copy-paste the audit logic into onboard.ts.\n    79→\n    80→**Legacy subcommand handling (AC #6):** The old `onboard` command had subcommands: `scan`, `coverage`, `audit`, `epic`. The new alias only needs to handle the bare `onboard` command (maps to `audit`) and provide a deprecation warning for `onboard scan`. The `coverage`, `audit`, and `epic` subcommands can be silently dropped — they were internal to the old onboarding pipeline.\n    81→\n    82→**Shared state removal:** The old `onboard.ts` maintained module-level shared state (`lastScanResult`, `lastCoverageResult`, `lastAuditResult`) with getter/setter exports. These are no longer needed. Check if any other files import `getLastScanResult()`, `getLastCoverageResult()`, `getLastAuditResult()`, or `resetLastScanResult()` before removing — the test file `onboard.test.ts` imports `resetLastScanResult` but that will be rewritten.\n    83→\n    84→**File size:** The rewritten `onboard.ts` should be dramatically smaller — from 478 lines to ~40-60 lines. Well under NFR9's 300-line limit.\n    85→\n    86→### What NOT To Do\n    87→\n    88→- **Do NOT delete `src/lib/scanner.ts`, `src/lib/epic-generator.ts`, `src/lib/onboard-checks.ts`, `src/lib/scan-cache.ts`, `src/lib/beads-sync.ts`** — other commands or tests may still use them. Only remove the imports from `onboard.ts`.\n    89→- **Do NOT modify `src/commands/audit.ts` behavior** — the audit command must continue to work identically. Only refactor to extract a shared handler if needed.\n    90→- **Do NOT add new npm dependencies** — this is pure refactoring.\n    91→- **Do NOT use `console.log` directly** — use output utilities from `src/lib/output.ts`.\n    92→\n    93→### Existing Code to Reuse\n    94→\n    95→- `src/commands/audit.ts` — `registerAuditCommand()`, the action handler logic to be shared\n    96→- `src/modules/audit/index.ts` — `runAudit()`, `generateFixStories()`, `addFixStoriesToState()` barrel exports\n    97→- `src/modules/audit/report.ts` — `formatAuditHuman()`, `formatAuditJson()` formatting\n    98→- `src/lib/onboard-checks.ts` — `runPreconditions()` (still needed for precondition check)\n    99→- `src/lib/output.ts` — `ok()`, `fail()`, `info()`, `warn()`, `jsonOutput()` for output formatting\n   100→\n   101→### Dependencies\n   102→\n   103→- **Depends on:** Story 3.1 (audit coordinator — `runAudit()`) — DONE. Story 3.2 (audit --fix — `generateFixStories()`) — DONE.\n   104→- **Depended on by:** None within this epic.\n   105→\n   106→### File Size Constraint\n   107→\n   108→Each new/modified file must be under 300 lines per NFR9.\n   109→- `src/commands/onboard.ts` — ~40-60 lines (down from 478, alias only)\n   110→- `src/commands/audit-action.ts` — ~80-100 lines (extracted shared handler, if created)\n   111→- `src/commands/__tests__/onboard.test.ts` — ~100-150 lines (simplified alias tests)\n   112→\n   113→### Previous Story Intelligence (Story 3.2)\n   114→\n   115→- **`runAudit()` returns `Promise<Result<AuditResult>>`** with `dimensions`, `overallStatus`, `gapCount`, `durationMs`.\n   116→- **`generateFixStories()` and `addFixStoriesToState()`** handle `--fix` logic.\n   117→- **`formatAuditHuman()` / `formatAuditJson()`** handle output formatting.\n   118→- **Commander.js** for CLI command registration with `.option()` and `.action()`.\n   119→- **`runPreconditions()`** from `src/lib/onboard-checks.js` for initialization check.\n   120→\n   121→### Git Intelligence\n   122→\n   123→The project uses Commander.js for CLI, vitest for testing, tsup for building. The existing `onboard.ts` is 478 lines with extensive functionality that is being replaced. The `audit.ts` command is 127 lines and well-structured.\n   124→\n   125→### References\n   126→\n   127→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-operational-excellence.md#Story 3.3] — Acceptance criteria\n   128→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-operational-excellence.md#FR16] — `onboard` becomes alias for `audit`\n   129→- [Source: src/commands/audit.ts] — Audit command to alias\n   130→- [Source: src/commands/onboard.ts] — Existing onboard command to replace\n   131→- [Source: src/index.ts] — Command registration\n   132→\n   133→### Project Structure Notes\n   134→\n   135→- Modified files: `src/commands/onboard.ts` (full rewrite as alias), `src/commands/__tests__/onboard.test.ts` (full rewrite)\n   136→- Possibly new file: `src/commands/audit-action.ts` (shared handler extraction)\n   137→- Possibly modified: `src/commands/audit.ts` (if refactored to use shared handler)\n   138→- No patches created in this story\n   139→- Module follows existing conventions: Commander.js, Result<T> returns, <300 line files\n   140→\n   141→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   142→## Verification Requirements\n   143→\n   144→- [x] Showboat proof document created (`docs/exec-plans/active/3-3-onboard-alias.proof.md`)\n   145→- [x] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence\n   146→- [x] Test coverage meets target (100% of all new code in src/)\n   147→\n   148→## Documentation Requirements\n   149→\n   150→- [x] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated (src/commands/AGENTS.md)\n   151→- [x] Exec-plan created in `docs/exec-plans/active/3-3-onboard-alias.md`\n   152→\n   153→## Testing Requirements\n   154→\n   155→- [x] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n   156→- [x] All I/O mocked (filesystem, subprocess, HTTP)\n   157→- [x] Coverage target: 100%\n   158→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n   159→\n   160→## Dev Agent Record\n   161→\n   162→### Implementation Plan\n   163→\n   164→- Extract `executeAudit()` from `audit.ts` into shared `audit-action.ts` module\n   165→- Refactor `audit.ts` to be a thin wrapper calling `executeAudit()`\n   166→- Rewrite `onboard.ts` as a 40-line alias calling `executeAudit()`\n   167→- Add deprecated `scan` subcommand with warning\n   168→- Rewrite test file to verify alias delegation, deprecation warning, and help output\n   169→\n   170→### 