{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Em2XRw3Hi7aBBMc3mqbUYk","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation.md`.\n\n**Summary of what was created:**\n\n- **Story 4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation** -- auto-discovered as the next backlog story in Epic 4 from `sprint-status.yaml`\n- **10 acceptance criteria** -- expanded from the 4 in the epic definition to cover all 6 rule categories individually plus edge cases (missing rules file, audit integration)\n- **6 tasks** with subtasks covering: rules markdown file, validator module, audit integration, barrel exports, unit tests, integration verification\n- **All ACs tagged `cli-verifiable`** -- every AC involves reading files, running the validator function, or running `codeharness audit`, all of which can be verified by CLI commands in a subprocess. None require workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions.\n\n**Key design decisions captured in Dev Notes:**\n- Validator uses regex line-by-line matching (not Docker AST)\n- Rules markdown is documentation; rules are hardcoded in validator\n- Replaces the existing inline FROM-check in `checkInfrastructure()` with the full 6-category `validateDockerfile()` call\n- New file: `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts` (~120-180 lines)\n- New file: `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` (~40-60 lines)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Ambiguity: rules file as code vs documentation.** Architecture Decision 5 says \"rules stored in `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md`\" and \"validator parses the Dockerfile and checks against rules\" -- this could imply the markdown is parsed programmatically. I chose the simpler interpretation: rules are hardcoded in the validator, markdown is reference documentation. The AC says \"When read, Then it lists required elements\" which supports this reading. If the intent was to parse the markdown as a DSL, the story would need rework.\n- **Workaround: expanded ACs beyond epic definition.** The epic only defined 4 ACs. I expanded to 10 to cover each of the 6 rule categories individually (AC #5-#8), the audit integration wiring (AC #9), and the fallback behavior (AC #10). This makes the story testable at a granular level but adds scope beyond what was explicitly in the epic.\n- **Risk: false positives in regex-based validation.** Rules like \"project binary on PATH\" are hard to detect reliably with regex -- a Dockerfile might install the binary via a mechanism the regex doesn't recognize. Noted in Dev Notes as acceptable (\"advisory tool, not security gate\").\n- **Observation:** `patches/infra/` directory doesn't exist yet. Task 1 creates the first file there. The `patches/` directory already has `observability/` and `dev/` etc. as precedent."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a16d745aee39d98e9 (use SendMessage with to: 'a16d745aee39d98e9' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 51839\ntool_uses: 25\nduration_ms: 148345</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d06dabce-ed3c-4abf-ad84-f2845532d39a","uuid":"d0e90881-1a49-4f1a-bfae-4789b926074f","timestamp":"2026-03-21T05:16:47.372Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a16d745aee39d98e9","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation.md`.\n\n**Summary of what was created:**\n\n- **Story 4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation** -- auto-discovered as the next backlog story in Epic 4 from `sprint-status.yaml`\n- **10 acceptance criteria** -- expanded from the 4 in the epic definition to cover all 6 rule categories individually plus edge cases (missing rules file, audit integration)\n- **6 tasks** with subtasks covering: rules markdown file, validator module, audit integration, barrel exports, unit tests, integration verification\n- **All ACs tagged `cli-verifiable`** -- every AC involves reading files, running the validator function, or running `codeharness audit`, all of which can be verified by CLI commands in a subprocess. None require workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions.\n\n**Key design decisions captured in Dev Notes:**\n- Validator uses regex line-by-line matching (not Docker AST)\n- Rules markdown is documentation; rules are hardcoded in validator\n- Replaces the existing inline FROM-check in `checkInfrastructure()` with the full 6-category `validateDockerfile()` call\n- New file: `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts` (~120-180 lines)\n- New file: `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` (~40-60 lines)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Ambiguity: rules file as code vs documentation.** Architecture Decision 5 says \"rules stored in `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md`\" and \"validator parses the Dockerfile and checks against rules\" -- this could imply the markdown is parsed programmatically. I chose the simpler interpretation: rules are hardcoded in the validator, markdown is reference documentation. The AC says \"When read, Then it lists required elements\" which supports this reading. If the intent was to parse the markdown as a DSL, the story would need rework.\n- **Workaround: expanded ACs beyond epic definition.** The epic only defined 4 ACs. I expanded to 10 to cover each of the 6 rule categories individually (AC #5-#8), the audit integration wiring (AC #9), and the fallback behavior (AC #10). This makes the story testable at a granular level but adds scope beyond what was explicitly in the epic.\n- **Risk: false positives in regex-based validation.** Rules like \"project binary on PATH\" are hard to detect reliably with regex -- a Dockerfile might install the binary via a mechanism the regex doesn't recognize. Noted in Dev Notes as acceptable (\"advisory tool, not security gate\").\n- **Observation:** `patches/infra/` directory doesn't exist yet. Task 1 creates the first file there. The `patches/` directory already has `observability/` and `dev/` etc. as precedent."}],"totalDurationMs":148345,"totalTokens":51839,"totalToolUseCount":25,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4231,"cache_read_input_tokens":46920,"output_tokens":687,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4231},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
